Below is a clean, production-safe step-by-step guide to onboard your existing Spark job to Airflow using SparkSubmitOperator + Method 2 (auto-loading variables from env_subscriber).

This keeps your environment variables centralized and avoids copying them into the DAG manually. ⚙️

⸻

Step 1 — Verify the env file exists on the Airflow node

Your variables file must be accessible from the Airflow machine (uti01).

Check:

ls /opt/telstra/omega/omega-common-files/env_subscriber

If it does not exist, copy it from the edge node:

scp edge-node:/opt/telstra/omega/omega-common-files/env_subscriber \
/opt/telstra/omega/omega-common-files/


⸻

Step 2 — Verify Spark client exists on Airflow node

Check:

which spark-submit

Expected:

/app/spark/spark3/bin/spark-submit

If not available, export it:

export SPARK_HOME=/app/spark/spark3
export PATH=$SPARK_HOME/bin:$PATH

Also make sure Hadoop configs exist:

ls /app/hadoop/hadoop/etc/hadoop

You should see:

core-site.xml
hdfs-site.xml
yarn-site.xml


⸻

Step 3 — Install the Spark provider in Airflow

Run as the Airflow user:

pip install apache-airflow-providers-apache-spark

Verify:

pip show apache-airflow-providers-apache-spark


⸻

Step 4 — Create Spark connection in Airflow

Open Airflow UI.

Admin → Connections → Add Connection

Fill:

Field	Value
Conn Id	spark_yarn
Conn Type	Spark
Host	yarn
Deploy mode	cluster

Save.

⸻

Step 5 — Create DAG file

Navigate to your DAG folder.

Your screenshots show:

cd /app/airflow/airflow/dags

Create file:

nano omega_iplogs_spark_dag.py


⸻

Step 6 — Add function to load env variables

Add this Python function at the top of the DAG file.

def load_env_file(file_path):
    env_vars = {}
    with open(file_path) as f:
        for line in f:
            line=line.strip()

            if not line or line.startswith("#"):
                continue

            if "=" in line:
                key,value=line.split("=",1)
                env_vars[key.strip()] = value.strip()

    return env_vars

This reads the env_subscriber file and converts it into a dictionary.

⸻

Step 7 — Load the env file

Add this below the function:

env_vars = load_env_file(
    "/opt/telstra/omega/omega-common-files/env_subscriber"
)

Now all variables from your file are available.

⸻

Step 8 — Create the Spark DAG

Add the DAG code.

from airflow import DAG
from airflow.providers.apache.spark.operators.spark_submit import SparkSubmitOperator
from datetime import datetime

with DAG(
    dag_id="omega_iplogs_streaming",
    start_date=datetime(2026,1,1),
    schedule_interval=None,
    catchup=False,
    tags=["spark","omega"]
) as dag:

    spark_job = SparkSubmitOperator(

        task_id="run_iplogs_stream",

        conn_id="spark_yarn",

        application="/opt/telstra/omega/subscriber-current/irqf.jar",

        java_class="com.telstra.omega.process.omegaProcessRequest",

        name="omega-irqf-internetRequest-iplogs",

        jars="""
/opt/telstra/omega/internetrequestquery/current/spark-internetRequest.jar,
/app/hbase/lib/hbase-client.jar,
/app/cluster-essentials/*
""",

        executor_memory="5g",
        executor_cores=2,
        num_executors=3,

        conf={

            "spark.streaming.backpressure.enabled":"true",

            "spark.streaming.kafka.maxRetries":"10",

            "spark.executor.heartbeatInterval":"60s",

            "spark.network.timeout":"600s",

            "spark.sql.parquet.compression.codec":"snappy",

            "spark.yarn.maxAppAttempts":"4",

            "spark.yarn.submit.waitAppCompletion":"false",

            "spark.debug.maxToStringFields":"2147483640"
        },

        env_vars=env_vars,

        verbose=True
    )

Save the file.

⸻

Step 9 — Fix file permissions

Ensure Airflow can read the DAG.

chown airflow:airflow /app/airflow/airflow/dags/omega_iplogs_spark_dag.py


⸻

Step 10 — Restart Airflow scheduler

systemctl restart airflow-scheduler

Or:

airflow scheduler restart


⸻

Step 11 — Verify DAG loads

Check via CLI:

airflow dags list

You should see:

omega_iplogs_streaming


⸻

Step 12 — Trigger the DAG

In Airflow UI:

DAGs → omega_iplogs_streaming → Trigger

Or CLI:

airflow dags trigger omega_iplogs_streaming


⸻

Step 13 — Verify Spark job

Check YARN:

yarn application -list

You should see your Spark application:

omega-irqf-internetRequest-iplogs


⸻

Step 14 — Verify streaming

Your config contains:

spark.yarn.submit.waitAppCompletion=false

So Airflow will:
	1.	submit job
	2.	mark task success
	3.	Spark job keeps running on YARN

This is expected for streaming jobs.

