When you have ~40 Spark --conf settings, putting them directly inside the DAG (like a large Python dictionary) becomes hard to maintain, error-prone, and messy. In production Spark + Airflow environments, teams usually externalize Spark configs and keep the DAG clean.

Below are the best approaches, and I’ll show what is most suitable for your job.

⸻

🥇 Best Option for Your Case: Use a Spark Properties File

Instead of writing 40 configs inside the DAG, move them to a Spark properties file.

Example file:

/opt/telstra/omega/config/iplogs_spark.properties

Example content:

spark.executor.memory=5g
spark.executor.instances=3
spark.executor.cores=2

spark.streaming.backpressure.enabled=true
spark.streaming.kafka.maxRetries=10

spark.executor.heartbeatInterval=60s
spark.network.timeout=600s

spark.sql.parquet.compression.codec=snappy

spark.yarn.maxAppAttempts=4
spark.yarn.submit.waitAppCompletion=false

spark.debug.maxToStringFields=2147483640

You can add all 40 configs here.

⸻

How to Use This in SparkSubmitOperator

Modify the DAG:

SparkSubmitOperator(
    task_id="run_iplogs_stream",
    conn_id="spark_yarn",

    application="/opt/telstra/omega/subscriber-current/irqf.jar",
    java_class="com.telstra.omega.process.omegaProcessRequest",

    properties_file="/opt/telstra/omega/config/iplogs_spark.properties",

    env_vars=env_vars,
    verbose=True
)

Spark will automatically read the configs from that file.

⸻

Advantages of Using properties_file

Advantage	Why it helps
Cleaner DAG	no 40-line dictionary
Easy tuning	change config without editing DAG
Version control	properties file can live in Git
Cluster portability	reuse across environments
Debugging	easier to inspect

This is the standard Spark practice.

⸻

